### CHAPTER XX.

1\. On the nature of rivers it says in revelation, that these two rivers
flow forth from the north, part from Albûr*z* *and* part from the
Albûr*z* of

<span id="page_75">p. 75</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> Aûharmazd <span
id="fr_379"></span>[1](#fn_376.md); one towards the west, that is the
Arag <span id="fr_380"></span>[2](#fn_377.md), *and* one towards the east,
that is the Vêh river. 2. After them eighteen rivers flowed forth from
the same source, just as the remaining waters have flowed forth from
them in great multitude; as they say that they flowed out so very fast,
one from the other, as when a man recites one Ashem-vohû <span
id="fr_381"></span>[3](#fn_378) of a series (pa*d*îsâr.md). All of those,
with the same water, are again mingled with these rivers, that is, the
Arag river *and* Vêh river. 4. Both of them continually circulate
through the two extremities of the earth, and pass into the sea; and all
the regions feast owing to the discharge (zahâk) of both, which, after
both arrive together at the wide-formed ocean, returns to the sources
whence they flowed out; as it says in revelation, that just as the light
comes in through Albûr*z* *and* goes out through Albûr*z* <span
id="fr_382"></span>[4](#fn_379.md), the

<span id="page_76">p. 76</span>

water also comes out through Albûr*z* and goes away through Albûr*z*. 5.
This, too, it says, that the spirit of the Arag begged of Aûharmazd
thus: 'O first omniscient creative power <span
id="fr_383"></span>[1](#fn_380.md)! from whom the Vêh river begged for the
welfare that thou mightest grant, do thou then grant *it* in my
quantity!' 6. The spirit of the Vêh river similarly begged of Aûharmazd
for the Arag river; *and* on account of loving assistance, one towards
the other, they flowed forth with equal strength, as before the coming
of the destroyer they proceeded without rapids, and when the fiend shall
be destroyed <span id="fr_384"></span>[2](#fn_381.md) they *will* again be
without rapids.

7\. Of those eighteen principal rivers, distinct from the Arag river
*and* Vêh river, and the other rivers which flow out from them, I *will*
mention the more famous <span id="fr_385"></span>[3](#fn_382.md): the Arag
river, the Vêh river, the Diglat <span id="fr_386"></span>[4](#fn_383.md)
river they call also again the Vêh river <span
id="fr_387"></span>[5](#fn_384.md), the Frât river, the Dâîtîk river, the
Dargâm river, the Zôndak river, the Harôî river, the Marv river, the
Hêtûmand river, the Akhôshir river, the Nâvadâ <span
id="fr_388"></span>[6](#fn_385.md) river, the Zî*s*mand river, the
Khve*g*and river, the Balkh river, the Mehrvâ river they call the Hendvâ
river, the Spêd <span id="fr_389"></span>[7](#fn_386.md) river, the
Rad <span id="fr_390"></span>[8](#fn_387.md) river which they call also the
Koir, the Khvaraê river which they call

<span id="page_77">p. 77</span>

also the Mesrgân, the Harhaz <span id="fr_391"></span>[1](#fn_388.md)
river, the Teremet river, the Khvanaîdi*s* <span
id="fr_392"></span>[2](#fn_389.md) river, the Dâra*g*a river, the Kâsîk
river, the *S*êd <span id="fr_393"></span>[3](#fn_390) ('shining'.md) river
Pêdâ-meyan *or* *K*atru-meyan river *of* Mokarstân.

8\. I *will* mention them also a second time: the Arag <span
id="fr_394"></span>[4](#fn_391.md) river is that of which it is said that
it comes out from Albûr*z* in the land of Sûrâk <span
id="fr_395"></span>[5](#fn_392.md), *in* which they call it also the Âmi;
it passes on through the land of Spêtos, which they also call Mesr, and
they call it there the river Niv <span id="fr_396"></span>[6](#fn_393.md).
9. The Vêh <span id="fr_397"></span>[7](#fn_394.md) river

<span id="page_78">p. 78</span>

passes on in the east, goes through the land of Sînd <span
id="fr_398"></span>[1](#fn_395.md), *and* flows to the sea in Hindûstân,
and they call it there the Mehrâ <span id="fr_399"></span>[2](#fn_396.md)
river. 10. The sources of the Frât <span id="fr_400"></span>[3](#fn_397.md)
river are from the frontier of Arûm, they feed *upon it* in Sûristân,
*and* it flows to the Diglat river; and of this Frât *it is* <span
id="fr_401"></span>[4](#fn_398.md) that they produce irrigation over the
land. 11. It is declared that Mânû*sk*îhar excavated the sources, *and*
cast back the water all to one place, as it says thus 'I reverence the
Frât, full of fish, which Mânû*sk*îhar excavated for *the benefit of*
his own soul, *and* he seized the water *and* gave to drink <span
id="fr_402"></span>[5](#fn_399.md),' 12. The Diglat <span
id="fr_403"></span>[6](#fn_400.md) river comes out from Salmân <span
id="fr_404"></span>[7](#fn_401.md), *and* flows to the sea in Khû*g*îstân.
13. The Dâîtîk <span id="fr_405"></span>[8](#fn_402.md) river is the river

<span id="page_79">p. 79</span>

*which* comes out from Aîrân-vê*g*, *and* goes out through the
hill-country <span id="fr_406"></span>[1](#fn_403.md); of all rivers the
noxious creatures in it are most, as it says, that the Dâîtîk river is
full of noxious creatures. 14. The Dargâm river is in Sûde. 15. The
Zend <span id="fr_407"></span>[2](#fn_404.md) river passes through the
mountains of Pan*g*istân, *and* flows away to the Haro river. 16. The
Haro <span id="fr_408"></span>[3](#fn_405.md) river flows out from the
Apârsên range <span id="fr_409"></span>[4](#fn_406.md). 17. The
Hêtûmand <span id="fr_410"></span>[5](#fn_407.md) river is in Sagastân, and
its sources are from the Apârsên range; this is distinct from that which
Frâsîyâ*v* conducted away <span id="fr_411"></span>[6](#fn_408.md). 18. The
river Akhôshir is in Kûmî*s* <span id="fr_412"></span>[7](#fn_409.md). 19.
The Zî*s*mand <span id="fr_413"></span>[8](#fn_410.md) river, in the
direction

<span id="page_80">p. 80</span>

of Soghd, flows away towards the Khve*g*and river. 20. The
Khve*g*and <span id="fr_414"></span>[1](#fn_411.md) river goes on through
the midst of Samarkand *and* Pargâna, and they call it also the river
Ashârd. 21. The Marv <span id="fr_415"></span>[2](#fn_412.md) river, a
glorious river in the east <span id="fr_416"></span>[3](#fn_413.md), flows
out from the Apârsên range. 22. The Balkh river comes out *from* the
Apârsên mountain of Bâmîkân <span id="fr_417"></span>[4](#fn_414.md), *and*
flows on to the Vêh <span id="fr_418"></span>[5](#fn_415.md) river. 23. The
Spêd <span id="fr_419"></span>[6](#fn_416.md) river is in Âtarô-pâtakân;
they say that Dahâk begged a favour <span
id="fr_420"></span>[7](#fn_417.md) here from Aharman and the demons. 24.
The Tort <span id="fr_421"></span>[8](#fn_418.md) river, which they call
also the Koir, comes out from

<span id="page_81">p. 81</span>

the sea of Gîklân <span id="fr_422"></span>[1](#fn_419.md), *and* flows to
the sea of Vergân <span id="fr_423"></span>[2](#fn_420.md). 25. The
Zahâvayi <span id="fr_424"></span>[3](#fn_421.md) is the river *which*
comes out from Âtarô-pâtakân, *and* flows to the sea in Pârs. 26. The
sources of the Khvaraê <span id="fr_425"></span>[4](#fn_422.md) river are
from Spâhân <span id="fr_426"></span>[5](#fn_423.md); it passes on through
Khû*g*îstân, flows forth to the Diglat <span
id="fr_427"></span>[6](#fn_424.md) river, and in Spâhân they call it the
Mesrkân <span id="fr_428"></span>[7](#fn_425.md) river. 27. The
Harhaz <span id="fr_429"></span>[8](#fn_426.md) river is in Taparîstân, and
its sources are from Mount Dimâvand. 28. The Teremet <span
id="fr_430"></span>[9](#fn_427.md) river flows away to the Vêh river. 29.
The Vendese*s* <span id="fr_431"></span>[10](#fn_428.md) river is in *that
part of* Pârs which they call Sagastân. 30. The Kâsak <span
id="fr_432"></span>[11](#fn_429) river comes out through a ravine (kâf.md)
in the province of Tûs <span id="fr_433"></span>[12](#fn_430.md), and they
call it there the Kasp river; moreover,

<span id="page_82">p. 82</span>

the river, which is there the Vêh, they call the Kâsak <span
id="fr_434"></span>[1](#fn_431.md); even in Sînd they call *it* the Kâsak.
31. The Pê*d*âk-mîyân <span id="fr_435"></span>[2](#fn_432.md), which is
the river *K*atru-mîyân, is that which is in Kangde*z* <span
id="fr_436"></span>[3](#fn_433.md). 32. The Dâra*g*a river is in
Aîrân-vê*g*, on the bank (bâr) of which was the dwelling of Pôrûshasp,
the father of Zaratû*s*t <span id="fr_437"></span>[4](#fn_434.md). 33. The
other innumerable waters and rivers, springs *and* channels are one in
origin with those <span id="fr_438"></span>[5](#fn_435.md); so in various
districts *and* various places they call *them* by various names.

34\. Regarding Frâsîyâ*v* <span id="fr_439"></span>[6](#fn_436.md) they
say, that a thousand springs were conducted away by him into the sea
Kyânsîh <span id="fr_440"></span>[7](#fn_437.md), suitable for horses,
suitable for camels, suitable for oxen, suitable for asses, both great
and small <span id="fr_441"></span>[8](#fn_438.md); and he conducted the
spring Zarînmand (or golden source), which is the Hêtûmand <span
id="fr_442"></span>[9](#fn_439.md) river they say, into the same sea; and
he conducted the seven navigable waters of the source of the
Va*k*aêni <span id="fr_443"></span>[10](#fn_440.md) river into the same
sea, *and* made men settle *there*.

